637CD292627D42B1A85E2D68A34C060F.description:
The student identifies and explains the meaning of different symbols of America. Symbols may
include, but are not limited to: HCG

4995D066EA2E48CB8F6D4CD6CB67B0AF.description:
The student tells stories about figures from American history through 2008, including stories from
their childhoods, lives as adults, and examples of their character. Figures may include, but are not
limited to: HC

18DFADE9F4D849D5840D589BF7837DC0.description: The student locates each of the following on a map: G

10E223D5874249C184D566D77259817F.description: The student can recite the “Pledge of Allegiance” from memory. C

E278A33FC87B4C9E9CEF698739E88E8B.description: The student can correctly use words related to work, including: E

41E7D9037B87453480D5A2DFD0E78BBE.description:
The student can give examples of virtues and actions related to hard work, personal potential,
and individual independence. CE

D9913579224E4936A9EB986CBD919DF8.description:
The student can give examples of treating others with and without respect for the equal
human dignity of each person. C

1AD25787CD3B4086B7281A812545C079.description: The student can give examples of rules and laws. C

2ACE72C6DF874A6C982C4AF30B1C2AB8.description:
The student can use the word “because” correctly in answer to questions of “why” and cause
and effect. H

3C741A8CE1574114B84B687438B2F392.description:
The student can use chronological and temporal terms correctly to narrate personal and
historical events, including now, long ago, in the future, last or next week, month, year, and
present, past, and future. H

91CD956A7A824E568FFC411A5D19575E.description:
The student can use a calendar correctly to identify days, weeks, months, and years and can
correctly reference “today,” “yesterday,” and “tomorrow.” H

3B94CA6689C446D1BFB4FD171E7B0CB3.description:
The student can use sequential terms correctly to narrate personal and historical events,
including first, next, last, before, and after. H

0CCB0B6DF34A4ABC8EFA0899D1EDAC7F.description:
The student can identify and describe differences in setting, housing, and clothing from
different time periods. H

8FE4F66865184D239D8665165439A927.description: The student can distinguish on a map between oceans, lakes, rivers, and mountains. G

D701E7CE300147C0BAB5ACEEB8A6D818.description:
The student can name his or her town, township or city, county, state or reservation, country,
and continent. G

C9EB2C517F43467BAE2CA593D12F956F.description: The student can identify and explain a map of the classroom. G

E3B0DB28545D4820BDBBBB042A66219F.description: The student can distinguish between a map and a globe. G

6FE97624231C43208E1FDD514F498688.description:
